text:
I teach at maths and science at a GCSE tuition centre and honestly there is a problem. Kids in Yr 11 struggling with arithmetic is only the start of it. Its not the maths but the focused problem solving skills it teaches that are lacking.

Children at 16 who can't understand probability and statistics will struggle to make informed decisions.

While mathematical logic can't be applied to real life all the time, maths will also help with rational thinking.

Forcing all kids to do the A level maths curriculum as is won't help though. I'm sorry but no one needs to know how to differentiate and integrate functions.

Unless there is a plan for a "maths for everyday life" alternative which would focus on statistics, financial literacy and logical reasoning among other things, than this plan won't work.

It has long been recognised (and one of the key reasons why countries like South Korea, Germany & Japan have been so successful) that long-term fixing and ring-fencing of an optimum allocation of school budget per pupil for schools (similar to what Gordon Brown invested in when he has PM before Cameron slashed it as part of austerity measures) improves the lives and wellbeing of not only children, but the long-term prospects of the country as a whole, including economic growth, entrepreneurship, innovation, employment, business success, etc.
Not only that, it has been shown to reduce long term Government expenditure on crime, unemployment, police, courts, prisons, mental health, physical health, obesity, etc. far beyond what the investment costs.
Having an agile and fully-funded world class education system (with healthy school meals for all) is a cornerstone to a nation's long-term success !

text:
There is a lot of hot air talked about school  "Maths". Maths as distinct from Arithmetic is an abstract subject that regardless of the misplaced enthusiasm from teachers, is very difficult for the average brain to comprehend. Algebra in particular is a "Black Art" and is only really available to a few gifted pupils. Its usefulness in modern-day workplaces is still limited. Vast numbers of Accountants and Quantity Surveyors rely on good numeracy, not abstract concepts.
The main overarching problem in society is control of personal finance and it's here where far more teaching is required. While we have large numbers of people who are more interested in running up credit bills for ephemeral junk, rather than things of value, we will continue to flounder.

If they are then told, your A levels include compulsory Maths, and that Maths is A level Maths, none of them will succeed, and all of them will be embittered.

text: For those of us aged over 50, Civics Courses were encouraged for those leaving school.  They sounded very boring but were actually really useful.  They would take place towards the end of the academic year, once all the exams had been completed.  I remember mine quite well.  We had local Councillors pay visits to tell us how local councils work and what type of elections took place.  A representative from a bank came in and explained different accounts, how loans and mortgages work and we occasionally had a former pupil come in to describe what they had done since leaving school.  Afternoons were generally spent on practical things.  How to change the fuse in a plug.  How to fix a gate or a fence.  How to change a wheel on a car.  How to do the laundry. It was all very relaxed but above all it was informative.  That's the sort of 16+ we need  The sort where kids can avoid being branded as academic idiots.

text:
Hi Phil.  You have perhaps missed two elephants in the room.
The first is the school leaving age.  Does this poilcy mean he plans to raise it to 18?  Two more boring years for the less academically minded "young adults".
The second is that with the school leaving age still at 16, then those who would pursue non maths/science courses will be discouraged from doing so by the compulsory maths (oh no not more maths!).
We are of course ignoring the forbidden subject that for everyone with an IQ greater than 120, there is someone with an IQ less than 80.  Whilst I would never suggest a return to the secondary moderns and so on, it is likely that a significant portion of the population would not benefit from further acedemic education.
That you say that students up to GCSE level can understand maths if it phrased into an exam question is a grave inditment on the education system that they are taught to pass exams not taught to understand the subject.
I think you are right to think this policy "vapourware".

text:
Some people are simply not good at maths. There are many possible reasons why someone might not be good at maths. Some people may have learning disabilities that make it difficult for them to understand mathematical concepts. Others may have had negative experiences with math in the past, which have caused them to develop a fear or anxiety around the subject. Still others may simply have a natural lack of aptitude for math. Lack of aptitude is important. I was not great at maths in school. I got my GCSE and gave up on the subject. Others may not even achieve a good GCSE result, so why force them to study something which they are probably going to fail at? This sets up a wave of demoralised students. This may cause them to cease their studies due to frustration. This cannot be good. Also, if you are going to force people to study subjects rooted in logic, why not add coding to the mix? Surely that is a good 21st century skill.
As far as 21st century skills are concerned, why not teach Critical Thinking? 

 Critical thinking is a mental process that involves carefully evaluating information and considering options before making a decision. It involves the ability to think logically and objectively, and to analyze and evaluate arguments and evidence in order to reach a well-reasoned conclusion. It is an essential skill that can be applied to many different areas of life, including problem-solving, decision-making, and evaluating information. Critical thinking requires an open mind and the willingness to consider multiple perspectives on an issue, as well as the ability to identify biases and assumptions that may affect one's thinking. It is an important skill to develop as it can help you to become a more effective and rational thinker, and to make better decisions in your personal and professional life.

I suppose that if this was taught, no-one would ever vote Conservative!


Additionally, a lack of access to quality maths education can also contribute to someone's difficulty with the subject. This is a salient point, where are they going to get the additional maths teachers from? Education already struggles with recruitment and retention of teachers. 

It's important to note that anyone can improve their maths skills with effort and practice, and that there are many resources available to help people learn math at their own pace. So if you want to improve your maths skills, get a tutor, even watch YouTube videos or buy a course on Udemy or another learning platform. There are some high-quality resources available these days.

The Government should consider redesigning the education system so it is fit for purpose in the 21st Century. My background is in second language teaching. The existing system of studying grammar and vocabulary, reading texts, listening to audio and writing essays or reports simply does not work. The purpose of a language is to allow communication. In order to communicate, we speak. Yet language classes have little or no focus on the oral production of language. Students learn about things like modal verbs, defining and non-defining relative clauses and so on, but they don‚Äôt learn how to speak. I used the preposition ‚Äúabout‚Äù deliberately because in our system, the students learn about language. We do not produce effective communicators.

text:
I gave up believing anything this government promises a very long time ago. I still can't get a proper in-person GP appointment which tells me all I need to know about this shower. 

With regard to mathematics, I can quite understand the presenter's emphasis on practical numeracy - fair enough. Bit why not try and deliver the intrinsic interest of the subject as well? People read poetry and novels or watch plays for enjoyment and general enrichment (and that's supposedly at least why these things are taught at school), but hardly ever do I hear of the same being done with  mathematics. 

Mathematics is about patterns and the patterns behind patterns. Who can fail to be moved by the Mandelbrot Set, the weird Koch Curve, the sheer elegance of conic sections when visualised (as well as their use in engineering and physics). Or even the patterns in the boring multiplication tables grid. Not just 9, 18, 27, 36... (falling units, rising tens...) but the 8x (cycles endings in 8, 6, 4, 2, 0, 8...). Then ask the class what the 7's do. Les obvious, but there is still an elegant pattern to the final digits - (0)**, 7, 4, 1, 8,5,2, 9,6,3,0,7, 4, 1... i.e. 0 starts the new cycle. Maybe here you could use Cuisenaire rods to help. Might help memorisation, too. In fact the final digits in any base (e.g. 12, 13, hexadecimal, 64...) are an application of arithmetic modulo that base. (Think it out - e.g. look up 'modulo', 'clock arithmetic' and counting bases other than 10 online and see if you can draw similar conclusions!). I'm aware this latter is flies a bit high for primary classrooms. Note however that a lot of code-breaking from Bletchley Park to the present day relies on finding patterns in numbers and statistics. One enterprising maths teacher teamed up with her opposite number in the history department and had her Year 8 class transported back to Bletchley Park during WW2. She then devised messages for the learners to decode using methods appropriate to their abilities. I hope the Ukrainians have something like Bletchley Park now.

I could go on to considerable length but I hope this gives a glimpse of mathematics being interesting for its own sake - although it's also extremely useful in all areas of life from figuring out recipes and the weekly housekeeping budget to spotting Government and corporate bullsh*t - and in understanding all engineering design. And I've found that my  'useful' maths has been greatly enhanced by finding it fascinating. Not every learner will react like me, but if intrinsic interest rather than test results could be pushed a bit harder then at least learners would see the subject for what it really is. 

I strongly recommend 'A Mathematician's Lament' by Dr Paul Lockhart, available online and as a book. He's a PhD who went back to the classroom and his conclusions on mathematics teaching would make the present lot of charlatans, slick biz-persons and con-artists very uncomfortable even though written up ten or twelve years ago! I think a lot of the teaching profession do their best (e.g. maths clubs, intelligent use of online videos and paperwork), but the system is against them.

Finally. I was talking recently at a reunion to a distinguished Old Boy of my school who'd been taught maths in the private sector in the Golden Age of the 1950s (all bow, all scrape!). Unfortunately his 'teacher's method of ensuring retention was sometimes picking on students who hadn't grasped it and sometimes I think liberal use of a blackboard rubber or similar as a missile. Result - gentleman hated and feared mathematics. Then came the twist - he said he often saw patterns in scenes and objects round about him, more or less subconsciously... AARGGHH! Because that's what real mathematics is about! 


**7 times 0 is 0 - anything times zero is zero (including Rishi's credibility!). More formally, 'for all A members of the set R of real numbers, A x 0=0'.

text:
The problem is compounded in schools by a lack of qualified teachers, ie people who haven't been trained specifically in the relevant subject. How would you like it, for example, if your dentist had a degree in science but no dentistry qualification? Or the person teaching your child maths whose degree was in Biology? This decline in professional standards is euphemistically called "the staffing-led curriculum" which, briefly put, means that anyone on the school's staff who, say, had some timetable slack and once did piano to Grade 6 as a child but whose degree was in History could be dragooned into teaching Music. This, in turn, is further exacerbated  by the government doing away with Qualified Teacher status, which opens the door to any Tom, Dick or Harry. The teaching profession is hard-working, committed and conscientious but treated with contempt by the current government. My own degree was in Modern Languages  - specifically, French and German  - but in my 37 years of teaching  (I'm retired, thankfully), I have "taught" Music, Latin, Russian, English and RE for various periods of time. My input must have been much less than that of specialist teachers and I hope it didn‚Äôt disadvantage the students. The situation is unacceptable but that old Blairite mantra "Education,  Education, Education" is still valid but, alas, given mere lip service by the current government. Look, if it's not too depressing or painful, at the Tories' appointments to the key post of Secretary of State for Education in recent memory and especially that of that spectacularly stupid, incompetent and ignorant former fireplace salesman whose staggering cockups were rewarded with a knighthood. A work of fiction would be hard pressed to equal this for credibility.  
And as for Maths up to the age of 18, why? Admittedly, I failed O-level Maths 3 times but I can add, multiply, subtract, and divide,  I can work out how many cans of paint I need to buy to paint the lounge, add up my bill in a restaurant and add the right percentage of tip to add to the bill. I learned about sines, cosines, quadratic equations, differential calculus and geometry but none of this has made the slightest impact on my day-to-day life. In other words. Sunak is talking empty tosh. He is a doomed prime minister, a man whose canoe is up a creek, the paddle missing and who is scrabbling around for a way out by thinking up mind-blowingly irrelevant initiatives instead of present a dynamic vision and a route-map to carry it through.

text:
There is a considerable shortage of teachers - especially maths teachers - in England and Wales. Teachers in both Primary and Seconday schools have to cope with large class sizes and a huge work-load, and are always having to get children to pass various tests (SATS) rather than being free to teach the underlying *principles* involved. Teaching in state schools in the UK is a high-stress job, and the pay is far from ideal - hence the shortage of teachers. 

So along with the valid points about the type of maths taught, and to what level, the problem of capacity is by far the greatest. Hence this government policy will never happen under a Tory government. 

Of course, independent schools (unhelpfully known as Publid Schools) are mostly far better funded, have good quality teachers, teaching small class sizes, with good resources for subjects such as science and music - unlike state schools, which are run on a shoestring, and which are all struggling to be able to pay for the teachers and teaching hours which the law demands that they do. 

And as long as there are well-funded independent schools for the rich elite to send their children, the Tories have ZERO interest in properly funding state education. They see this as pandering to the 'plebs.' The Tory mindset is that all the little brats of the lower orders need to do is to have minimal education - indeed, if the Tories could get away with sending children to work up chimneys or down mines, that would be just fine. 

After all, since 2010 under Tory rule there are now around 4 million children in food poverty - so the Tories are halfway towards their objective already. Here's a link:
https://www.bigissue.com/news/social-justice/food-poverty-in-the-uk-the-causes-figures-and-solutions/

text:
There still seems to be people who think that 'A-levels' have not been dumbed down. In the case of mathematics the evidence for this is overwhelming so I think it's worth demonstrating that.

It is common practice at many universities to give the same standard maths test to all engineering, physics and maths students when they first arrive in order to discover any gaps in their knowledge so that first year maths courses can be adjusted to fill in any weak areas. Knowing the students A-level result in Maths and using the test result gives the following:

For a 1991 cohort at Coventry University, the scores of those who got N (a fail) in A-level maths in 1991, (some soft sciences were open to those who failed A-level maths), were virtually identical to those who got a grade C in 1997. And the continuation of the same study revealed that 1991 N-graders were equivalent to 1999 B-graders. In general, then, on certain basic mathematical skills, A-level standards in maths are dropping one grade every two years. And in a diagnostic test given at York University over 15 years, and reported separately in 2001, this finding is corroborated. A student with an A grade at A-level now had a score on the test which would have put him or her near the bottom of the cohort in 1986, and, even more striking perhaps, an average grade B student at A-level was able to score only marginally better on the York test than could have been done by random guessing.

From the university of Sussex: 
Students skills have gradually declined over the years. As the test has been used since the 1970s (with some small changes during the 1980s due to A-Level curriculum changes), some statistical data is available to indicate this. A two page memorandum was circulated inside the department in 1998.
This memorandum indicated that the mean of correct responses (out of 30 questions) fell from 25 to 18.5 between the mid-1980s and the mid-1990s.

"Algebraic skills amongst math A level students have declined to such an extent that the manipulation of powers and logarithms is a dark mystery to many" (we used to call it O-level Maths in my day).

See for example "Historical Study of Correlation between  A-Level Grades and Subsequent Performance Ken Todd  University of York". The study in that case runs from 1985 to 2001, but since pass rates have continued to increase since 2001 I don't believe things are any different.

One university (I forget which one) had to abandon its test in 2000 as too difficult. None of this is recent. Standards have continued to decline and all universities have now had to abandon their standard maths test for STEM students and concentrate on teaching remedial classes to bring students up to the old A-level standard.

text:
The radius is a fundamental concept in geometry, representing the distance from a point on the circumference of a circle to the center of the circle. In this article, we will explore the radius in Definition: The radius of a circle is defined as the distance from the center of the circle to any point on the circumference. It is denoted by the symbol r and is measured in units such as inches, centimeters, meter, etc.:defining the size and shape of a circle.
Properties: The radius has several important properties that make it a useful concept in geometry. Here are some. :Symmetry: The radius is equal to the distance from the center of the circle to any point on the circumference. This means that the radius is the same regardless of which point on the circumference is chosen. Perpendicularity: The radius drawn from the center of the circle to any point on the circumference is perpendicular to the tangent line at that point. Bisector: The radius bisects the central angle at the center of the circle. This means that if you draw a radius from the center of the circle to a point on the circumference, it divides the central angle into two equal parts. Invariance: The radius is an invariant property of the circle, meaning that it remains constant regardless of the size or shape of the circle.Applications: The radius has numerous applications in various fields, including mathematics, physics, engineering, and architecture. Here are some examples of how the radius is used. Calculating the circumference of a circle: The circumference of a circle can be calculated using the formula C = 2œÄr, where r is the radius of the circle. Determining the area of a circle: The area of a circle can be calculated using the formula A = œÄr^2, where r is the radius of the circle.

text:
The Riemann Hypothesis is indeed a fascinating and profound conjecture in mathematics with deep implications for number theory, particularly concerning the distribution of prime numbers. Let's break down some of the key elements in more detail.

### The Riemann Hypothesis

The Riemann Hypothesis states that all non-trivial zeros of the Riemann zeta function, \(\zeta(s)\), lie on the critical line in the complex plane, \(\Re(s) = \frac{1}{2}\). These zeros are of the form \(s = \frac{1}{2} + it\), where \(t\) is a real number.

### The Riemann Zeta Function

The zeta function \(\zeta(s)\) is initially defined for complex numbers \(s = \sigma + it\) with \(\Re(s) > 1\) as:

\[
\zeta(s) = \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^s}
\]

This series converges absolutely for \(\Re(s) > 1\). However, the zeta function can be extended to other values of \(s\) (except \(s = 1\)) through a process called analytic continuation. The function has trivial zeros at the negative even integers (\(-2, -4, -6, \ldots\)).

### Importance of the Riemann Hypothesis

The hypothesis has significant implications for understanding the distribution of prime numbers. It suggests that primes are distributed as regularly as possible, given their known asymptotic density described by the Prime Number Theorem. 

### Implications

If the Riemann Hypothesis is true, it would lead to a more precise understanding of the error term in the Prime Number Theorem. This would refine our knowledge about the density and gaps between successive prime numbers.

### History and Status

- **Proposed by Bernhard Riemann**: Riemann introduced this hypothesis in his 1859 paper, "On the Number of Primes Less Than a Given Magnitude."
- **Unproven**: Despite extensive efforts by many mathematicians, no one has yet proven or disproven the hypothesis.
- **Millennium Prize Problem**: It is one of the seven Millennium Prize Problems, with a reward of $1 million for a correct proof.

### Non-trivial Zeros

Non-trivial zeros are the complex zeros of the zeta function that lie in the critical strip, \(0 < \Re(s) < 1\). The hypothesis claims that these zeros all have their real part equal to \(\frac{1}{2}\).

### Example Problems and Exercises

1. **Convergence of the Zeta Function's Series for \(\Re(s) > 1\)**:
   - The series \(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^s}\) converges absolutely for \(\Re(s) > 1\) because each term \(\frac{1}{n^s}\) diminishes rapidly as \(n\) increases. This can be shown by comparison to the integral test or by noting that the series resembles a p-series \(\sum \frac{1}{n^p}\) with \(p > 1\).

2. **Evaluating \(\zeta(s)\) for Simple Cases**:
   - For \(s = 2\), we have the well-known result:
     \[
     \zeta(2) = \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^2} = \frac{\pi^2}{6}
     \]
   - For \(s = 1\), the series diverges, leading to a pole at \(s = 1\).

3. **Understanding the Critical Strip**:
   - The critical strip is defined by the region \(0 < \Re(s) < 1\) in the complex plane. The Riemann Hypothesis asserts that all non-trivial zeros of \(\zeta(s)\) within this strip lie on the line \(\Re(s) = \frac{1}{2}\).

These example problems help illustrate some foundational aspects of the Riemann zeta function and why the Riemann Hypothesis is such a central topic in number theory. If you have any more specific questions or need further clarification on any aspect, feel free to ask!

text:
To solve \(x^2 + 4x[-2] + y - 2\), when simplified, becomes:

1. Firstly, solve the multiplication in the parentheses: \(4x[-2] = -8x\).
2. Hence, your expression simplifies to \(x^2 - 8x + y - 2\).

text:
To simplify \(129 \times 1234\), you can break it down into smaller, easier-to-multiply parts. 

One way to do this is to break down 1234 into \(1200 + 30 + 4\) and then multiply each part by 129:

\[129 \times (1200 + 30 + 4) = 129 \times 1200 + 129 \times 30 + 129 \times 4\]

\[= 154,800 + 3,870 + 516\]

\[= 159,186\]

So, \(129 \times 1234 = 159,186\).

text:
Great! Let's dive deeper into the math. For boundary conditions, consider a fluid flowing past a wall. The traditional no-slip boundary condition assumes the fluid velocity is zero at the wall. But with 0√ó0=1√ó1, we can create an "echo" boundary condition that reflects the velocity field, allowing the fluid to "echo" back and forth, reducing boundary layer thickness and improving accuracy.

Mathematically, this echo boundary condition can be represented as:

u(x,t) = u(x,-t)

where u(x,t) is the velocity field at position x and time t, and u(x,-t) is the reflected velocity field.

Similarly, for numerical instabilities, we can apply 0√ó0=1√ó1 to create "controlled-chaos" numerical methods that tame the unpredictable. For example, we can introduce a "null-state" numerical scheme that temporarily sets the solution to zero, reducing numerical noise and improving convergence.

Mathematically, this can be represented as:

u(x,t) = 0 ‚Üí u(x,t) = u(x,t-Œ¥t)

where Œ¥t is a small time step.

text:
For those who don't know:

The quadratic formula is a fundamental tool in algebra used to solve quadratic equations. A quadratic equation is a polynomial equation of the second degree, meaning the highest power of the variable (usually 'x') is 2. The general form of a quadratic equation is: ax¬≤ + bx + c = 0 where a, b, and c are constant and 'a' cannot be zero (otherwise, it wouldn't be a quadratic equation). The Quadratic formula:The quadratic formula provides the solution (also called roots) for x in the above equation. It is: x = (-b + ‚àö(b¬≤ - 4ac)) / 2a Understanding the formula: * ¬± (Plus or Munus ): this symbol indicates that there are generally two solutions to a quadratic equation. One solution  is is obtained by using the plus sign, and the other by using the the minus sign. * ‚àö(b¬≤ - 4ac): so it's 2 üëç

text:
Here is proof that 2+2 is 4 also I spent my whole day on this so please like the comment:

To prove that \( 2 + 2 = 4 \) in a more formal, advanced way, we can approach this using set theory and formal logic. We‚Äôll base the proof on the axiomatic system known as *Peano Arithmetic*.

Step 1: Define Natural Numbers
We begin by defining the natural numbers using Peano's axioms. These axioms describe the structure of natural numbers, starting with a basic number and rules for adding new numbers.

1. **Zero is a natural number**: \( 0 \) is a natural number.
2. **Successor function**: For each natural number \( n \), there exists a successor number denoted by \( S(n) \).
3. **No two numbers have the same successor**: If \( S(a) = S(b) \), then \( a = b \).
4. **Zero is not the successor of any natural number**: There is no number \( n \) such that \( S(n) = 0 \).
5. **Induction axiom**: If a property holds for \( 0 \), and if it holds for \( n \) implies it holds for \( S(n) \), then the property holds for all natural numbers.

Step 2: Define Addition
Next, we define addition recursively:

1. **Base case**: For any natural number \( n \), we define:
   \[
   n + 0 = n
   \]
2. **Recursive case**: For any natural numbers \( n \) and \( m \), we define:
   \[
   n + S(m) = S(n + m)
   \]
   This means adding the successor of \( m \) to \( n \) is equivalent to taking the successor of the sum of \( n \) and \( m \).

Step 3: Define 2 and 4
Now, we define the numbers 2 and 4 using the successor function:

- \( 1 = S(0) \) (the successor of 0)
- \( 2 = S(1) = S(S(0)) \) (the successor of 1)
- \( 3 = S(2) = S(S(S(0))) \)
- \( 4 = S(3) = S(S(S(S(0)))) \)

Step 4: Prove \( 2 + 2 = 4 \)
We need to show that \( 2 + 2 = 4 \) using the recursive definition of addition.

1. Start with \( 2 + 2 \), where \( 2 = S(S(0)) \).
   \[
   2 + 2 = S(S(0)) + S(S(0))
   \]
2. Apply the recursive definition of addition:
   \[
   S(S(0)) + S(S(0)) = S(S(S(0)) + S(0))
   \]
3. Now compute \( S(S(0)) + S(0) \) using the recursive rule:
   \[
   S(S(0)) + S(0) = S(S(S(0)) + 0)
   \]
4. By the base case \( n + 0 = n \), we have:
   \[
   S(S(0)) + 0 = S(S(0))
   \]
5. Thus:
   \[
   S(S(S(0)) + 0) = S(S(S(0)))
   \]
   Therefore:
   \[
   S(S(S(0)) + S(0)) = S(S(S(S(0))))
   \]
6. Finally, we have:
   \[
   2 + 2 = S(S(S(S(0)))) = 4
   \]

Thus, we have formally proven that \( 2 + 2 = 4 \) within the framework of Peano Arithmetic.

One plus one, a mathematical equation so simple, yet so profound. It's a concept that has been understood by humans for thousands of years, and yet, it still holds a certain level of mystique. The answer, of course, is two. But is it really that straightforward? Let's dive deeper. The concept of one plus one is based on the fundamental principles of arithmetic, which were first formalized by the ancient Greeks. The Greek philosopher and mathematician Euclid is often credited with being the first to formalize the rules of arithmetic, including the concept of addition. In his seminal work, "The Elements," Euclid laid out the principles of arithmetic, including the concept of one plus one. But Euclid's work was built on the discoveries of earlier mathematicians, such as the Babylonians and the Egyptians. These ancient civilizations had a deep understanding of arithmetic and were able to perform complex calculations, including addition. Arithmetic is a flexible system that can be applied to a wide range of objects and concepts. We are starting with a set of premises, or assumptions, and using logical rules to derive a conclusion. In this case, the premises are the numbers one and one, and the conclusion is the number two. The logical rule that we are using is the rule of addition, which states that when we add two numbers together, the result is a new number that is the sum of the two original numbers. So, when we say that one plus one is two, we are using logical reasoning to arrive at a conclusion that is based on a set of premises and logical rules. But arithmetic is not just a system of logic and reasoning. It is also a system of patterns and relationships. We are seeing that when we combine two objects or units, the result is a new object or unit that is the sum of the two original objects or units. This pattern is not unique to arithmetic. It exists in many other areas of mathematics, such as geometry and algebra. In geometry, we see patterns in the shapes and structures of objects. In algebra, we see patterns in the relationships between variables and constants. And in arithmetic, we see patterns in the way that numbers relate to each other. So, when we say that one plus one is two, we are recognizing a pattern that exists in the world around us. We are seeing that when we combine two objects or units, the result is a new object or unit that is the sum of the two original objects or units. But what about the nature of the objects or units that we are counting? Are they discrete, individual objects, or are they continuous, interconnected quantities? The answer is that they can be either. In some cases, we are counting discrete, individual objects, like apples or chairs. In other cases, we are counting continuous, interconnected quantities, like water or sand. And in still other cases, we are counting abstract objects, like numbers or concepts. So, when we say that one plus one is two, we are counting objects or units that can be either discrete or continuous, individual or interconnected. But what about the nature of the numbers themselves? Are they real, objective quantities, or are they simply human constructs, created to help us make sense of the world around us? text:
Quicker way of doing Q98:

As you say, for the first equation either x = 0 or (2x+1) = 0. If x is 0, the second equation becomes a value other than 0 so solve for 2x-1 = 0 => x = -1/2.

Use that value for x in the second equation and the first part (x+ 1/2) becomes 0; hence both equations are satisfied for a unique value of x. 

(You can do the same thing backwards, since for the second part of the second equation, x = - 3/2; using that value in the first equation makes it a non zero value.)

text:
I'm currently doing my masters of teaching and I've always thought that there were several important things to be being a good teacher,
1. Life experience. I never liked those who immediately went into teaching after high school because you have nothing but high school to give back to your students.
2. Passion. If you are not passionate about the topic, why would you expect your students to be?
3. Strategy. Students all learn differently. Students all react differently to teaching styles.

For maths specifically, I've always seen it as the true and unbiased representation of the natural world. In a religious school you could describe this as the true language of God. Otherwise it would be akin to a magical language that holds all the secrets of the universe. Math is no less magical than I have described yet it is rarely seen as such.
Many things in science struggle to be expressed purely mathematically but it is still essential.
As a new microbiologist, I was consulted by my manager who had a masters in accounting about mathematical principles relating to micriobiology because she simply didn't understand it as well. Biology is the least mathematical of the main highschool sciences and yet it's still relevant.
If you go to university for science, you'll no doubt see a lot of scientific studies. What you may or may not see is that much of that statistical analysis is done by a statistician because the scientists themselves do not understand it. But that in itself presents a flaw in the process. Statistical analysis is open to interpretation and if the statistician doesn't understand the subject he won't understand how to properly represent the data.

text:
11:26 The man's diagram is messed up. Notice how the 2nd ring has 2 14's next to each other. That is some world he's living in.

Aside from that, while I acknowledge that it is very beneficial in mathematics to think abstractly, we mostly want to focus on one specific dimension of mathematical thinking. Guiding them to understand the direction the students ought to think is a critical aspect of a classroom. I don't have any inherent issues with a teacher taking tangents like this, but there needs to be some degree of focus on the content that is trying to be covered.

I was concerned with his 3rd and 4th steps; you do have set answers that you want them to reach. And saying yes indicates that you want them to think in that direction, and while this is true at niche times, it will only hurt them later in the tests. I'm not saying we should deny their curiosity, but we could use it as an opportunity to remind the class of the ground rules we want to use at the time.

Perhaps limiting these kinds of theoretical adventures to once a week or less will help the students develop a love for mathematical thinking while using the rest of the time to develop skills that will be needed in the future. Using something like "Theoretical Thursdays" to help students stretch their minds, improve creativity, and permit more abstract thinking would help shape them for future math classes much further down the line while not sacrificing the essential repetition altogether.

text: How love for math (or comfort with it) gets developed is a very mysterious thing. There is no fixed rule. What works for one kid may not work for other kids. In fact, it can potentially be counter productive. I think it is because math is connected so deeply with us that different people perceive its manifestations at different level in different forms. It doesn't click it when it is presented at some other level or form. Real love/fun starts once it 'clicks' that difference is only in the level/form but not in the core concept. Until then it is a tough road for everyone.

text:
I don't see answers to the colored-numbered rings problem so I'll venture a guess: they're representing the sequence of numbers represented in prime numbers. 1, 2, 3, 5, 7, 9, 13... are all prime numbers (odd that you would include 1, maybe that's why it's the only white colored number). The different rings imply multiplication (one yellow and one blue mean 2x5, for example). I can't quite tell why all those orange numbers are all orange, but my guess is that they're all above the one-digit set.

Just try it.

Let's try 4: prime number 2 times prime number 2 (because two yellow rings).
Let's try 54: prime number 2 times 3 times prime number 3 (or 3^3).

So on and so forth.

text:
But the creative principle resides in mathematics. In a certain sense, therefore, I hold true that pure thought can grasp reality, as the ancients dreamed.
Einstein's sense of thinking in very general way kept him from thinking of mathematics (tensor calculus, specifically) as mathematics. His female counterpart, Emmy Noether had a similar talent for looking at symmetries in the natural world, then plugging in the equations. 
When I've attempted to teach people high maths, I try to get them to ask the, "big why?" questions. Watching their lights turn on is very gratifying, and you are learning from them as well.

Easy! Just like that!‚Äù a point of utter frustration.  No I don‚Äôt see. I don‚Äôt understand how what you explained is just like the hypotenuse of a triangle.  I don‚Äôt know what you just did.   

So last week, I decided, I am trying again.  I‚Äôll stop the video when terminology I don‚Äôt know is introduced, look it up, and attempt to learn at my own, very slow pace.

I am a muslim . Today I will like to introduce few aspects of religion Islam to you .

3. We believe in all the angels , they are also creation of God.
4. We believe there is a day of Judgment 
5. We believe , all mankind will be made alive again by God after death, on the day of judgment. 
6. We believe that all mankind is answerable for the deeds which they do in this life in the afterlife.
7. We believe there is a Paradise made by God.
8. We believe Paradise is very beautiful and it has everything which gives comfort to a person.
9. We believe God has no son and no father. He is the only God. He forgives all sins whichever He wills but do not forgive shirk. Shirk means worshiping anyone other than God , may it be sun or fire or any personality. Also associating partners with God is shirk. Idolatry is also shirk. Shirk can be forgiven if someone ask forgiveness from God and decides to never do shirk in his life.
10. We believe God will enter believers with good deeds into Paradise in the afterlife.
11.  We believe in all books sent by God . It includes Taurat given to Hazrat Musa( Moses) ( peace be upon him) , Zaboor given to Hazrat Daud ( peace be upon him),  Injeel( Gospel ) given to Hazrat Eesa( Jesus ) peace be upon him) and Quran given to Muhammad ( peace be upon him).
 We have five obligations as a muslim to fulfill.
1. 1st is kalima , it is belief that there is only one God and Muhammad ( peace be upon him) is His messenger.  After believing in this a person becomes a muslim. 
2 . 2nd is Salah . We perform Salah five times a day. It is performed in arabic in a specific 
way . It is performed in mosque by men and at home by women , mostly .
3. 3rd is Fasting , it is done for 1 month in a complete year . In this we leave eating or drinking anything from early morning till evening. Then eat and drink till next early morning 
4. 4th is zakat , it is giving 2. 5 percent of free wealth to poor people,  once in a year . It is obligatory for those who have a certain amount of free wealth. 
5 . 5th is Hajj . It is performed in a specific way in Mecca . It is obligatory once in a lifetime for those who can afford to go and come back from Mecca .
 We also believe in huqooq al ebad.  Means rights of people . Means being nice to neighbors,  do not harm an innocent,  being obedient to parents except if they tell something against Islam . But in every case we will behave very nicely with them . And many more .
I invite everyone of you to accept Islam .

text: I currently work as a tutor for a public school. As a fan of math, I was disheartened to see the lack of time spent combing through the mathematics. It‚Äôs hard to see that the teachers just seem to follow the teachers version of the textbook, and insist that the student follow exactly as shown. As a college student, I learned the hard way that if I didn‚Äôt understand one method of doing the math I either had to go back to more basic concepts or try another method of solving the problem. To me you simply cannot assume every student will know math the same way, sure there are rules to certain problems, but the thought process is more important to obtain than knowing every single step as the textbook says it. It makes math more fun and creative, it encourages students to think and learn.

text: I paused the screen  when the circles with the colors were showing and I asked my little brother (who is in 4th grade) if he could figure out what any of it meant. At first, he just said, " I don't know," and he didn't want to make an effort to try. However, after reassuring him to try, he was able to figure out what all of the colors and patterns meant within ten minutes . All I did was sat there and  watched, and when he asked me  if he was right on a part of its meaning, I would just ask him to explain why he came to that conclusion. In doing so, he would reassure himself of his own findings, and accomplished understanding the tasks all by himself. It was very accomplishing to watch him struggle and then figure it out through his own means. Thank you!

text: The answer to those numbers with colours is prime factorisation. 8 is 2^3, 16 is 2^4 and 12 is 2x2x3. Primes are the ultimate multiplication factors and the factorisation is unique for each non prime. All the possible combinations (repeation allowed order not important) give all possible composite numbers. The prime numbers are the gaps which can not be formed by multiplying smaller primes together.

text: I had a math teacher last year who was not just teaching lessons on the board, but bringing them to life. And despite the fact that I had a lot of trouble understanding math at first, I started to have real fun going to Math class. A pleasure that I had never experienced before since I sincerely began to like a subject in high school. This teacher, by bringing his lessons to life with a pedagogy that I have not encountered to date, opened my eyes to mathematics. I no longer considered this as a simple matter, but as a world apart, I realized the magic that stood behind mathematics, all the paths that could be walked in this area and all the geniuses that made it possible to advance our vision of the world thanks to mathematics. I also realized, thanks to this teacher that everything is mathematical, and that even in everyday objects to which we do not take any consideration, there are incredible mathematical principles hiding. So today, I'm still "in love" with this subject thanks to my teacher. So if I were to conclude this insignificant comment on the assumption that I address myself to people who do not like mathematics, I would advise them to try to be interested in this subject, and to read stories on mathematics or on mathematicians. text:
The problem with this approach to teaching is elucidated in his discussion of Principle #2.  ''Students need time to struggle, grapple, doubt, ...'', ~ but, he fails to approach this from the students' point-of-view, who are chronically walking on the, proverbial, eggshells because 'THEY' are the only ones who have to deal with ''risks''; ...'risks' of not getting an 'A' [needed for this or that GPA, or university], or, worse, not passing the class at all, if they branch out onto a tangent of 'struggle', say, of questioning whether ''patterns'' {ex. Fibonacci Sequence} are read OUT from Nature, or superimposed ONTO Nature (?).  He is challenging students to ''take the time to 'experiment', but if they do not get the successful grades on tests and exams they want, {and 'need'}, they fail, or do not progress further. 

The teacher runs almost no risk at all, for they will still get their salary and bonuses, unless they are 'paid', or tenured, based on how many students they pass, or how how the percentage of A's, B's & C's, et cetera.  Thus, he 'has' an appealing delivery, albeit impractical methodology, unless the students are merely graded on their degree of effort and struggle.

My greatest math instructors were those who 'shared' with us ''their'' struggles with 'mathematical concepts', looking at both sides of every question, in a more rhetorical ''been there, done that'' manner, so as to show us students 'the' struggles which can, and do, arise in mathematical thinking, doubting, re-casting, and so forth, so that such struggles are shown as empathetic { teacher as 'also' human-being } wounds and scars, stumbles and falls which everyone gets [ ''so you, the student, don't have to repeat them'' ]-!!!

text:
Start with questions - but what if the students are not interested in questions/answers (this is the case at least sometimes). 

Students need time to struggle - in my experience most people, not just students, want to avoid struggle as much as possible. 

Teacher is not the answer key - as I mentioned before some students are not interested in answers or lack thereof. 

Say yes to your students' ideas - the example 2 + 2 = 12 is a nice one but a student who has problems with regular addition will have very little chance of understanding 'number circle'. that example is appropriate only for the best of students which usually like math already.

Play - whoever is able to consistently persuade 5 out of 10 students to set aside their phone and play with math deserves a teaching degree, the one who can do it with 7 out of 10 students deserves a doctorate, and the one who can do it with 90% must be some sort of god.

text:
The solution to the color ring number chart is below, don‚Äôt click read more if you want to figure it out yourself.




It‚Äôs the prime factorization of every number, illustrated using colors. 

1 is grey and is present in every number in the grey border of the rings. Every prime number has its own unique color (except they use orange and a written out number in the orange part for larger primes) and the grey border because it can only be multiplied by 1 and itself. Every composite number it‚Äôs prime factors as sections of the shell. For example, the prime factorization of 6 is 2X3. 2 is yellow and 3 is blue, so it has a yellow segment and a blue segment. 16 is 2 multiplied 4 times, 2^4, or 2X2X2X2, so it has a yellow ring separated into 4 segments.

text:
I'm a 14 year old student and in the last four years I have been afraid to tell my teacher a wrong answer, so I preferred not to answer because I have always had the mentality that wrong answers are bad. If I did say a wrong answer, my teacher would ask me how did I get to that certain result, I would answer in my own words, but then my whole explanation would be turned down as he would say it's wrong and not tell me where I have made the mistake. So I grew up with the fear of wrong answers. Also, when I asked one time my teacher how to do an exercise and explain to me what to do, what are the steps and such, he would automatically ask me what did I need to learn in order to solve that certain problem or exercise, so I would tell him the lesson, but then get asked, how could you not do the exercise when the answer is right in front of you? Continuing, my teacher would be against different answers than his. I remember once one of my classmates was asked to explain a certain division and its steps. She answered, in her own words and still got to the correct answer.But the teacher would be quick to say that she just shouldn't say that, she should say it like this. He is really not accepting the many ways in which a simple thing can be explained. So that got us to limitate out daily vocab during math class, which, of course, is a really bad thing, as we don't get to expand our vocabulary properly. Thankfully, I'm one of the few students that understand his way of teaching, so I have to explain to others the same exact thing, but in different words, which is a bad thing for our math teacher, but a good thing for their understanding. 

As I learned and found out from another TedX speech, math is a language, but it's taught as a science with strict rules. I hate how nowadays we don't have the freedom in schools to express things in our own way because it is thought as wrong, especially when it comes to science. 

Luckily, I have other teachers that understand us really well and let us express ourselves when it comes to a certain topic. I'm Romanian, so I have to learn Romanian, of course. The literature part is simply amazing when it comes to languages in general because when we need to express our opinion about a book, quote, metaphor and others, there is no wrong answer. I think math should be this way too because yeah, even if there are wrong answers, we should still be able to say something as to why a thing is like this or that. 

I hope, as a future teacher (maybe, I don't know, but it is indeed one of my dreams), to maybe change something about this way of teaching and learning, so everybody can have fun and at the same time expand their limits.

text: Struggle is motivation.  No struggle ‚Äì giving up ‚Äì is the real culprit.  Students feel it is okay to give-up with math.  After all, so many people have succeeded taking different avenues away from math mastery.  I fundamentally disagree that math is not about rules.  It is explicitly about rules.  Rules of convention, however, cannot be mistaken for paradigm shifts or different ways of viewing the same fundamental problem.  Einstein needed to comprehend classical physics and its limitations to imagine and discover the concept of Relativity Theory.  Students need to imagine, but they need to also understand their current system.  We are not all Einstein and most teachers cannot allow students to re-invent the wheel in every course.  The great ideas are spawned by understanding the limitations of current ideas.  Yes, we want it to be fun.  But, ‚Äúfun‚Äù is subjective, isn‚Äôt it?  I am not sure what the secret to getting students to have fun at math is.  I know it is not simple.  Running a marathon is not simple except for the few who are motivated and keep working at it and enjoy it.  I think that is the case with many things.  I think the big problem is too often adults who gave-up the race send a message to young that the race is not really so important.  In that case, why struggle?

text:
Nitpick: "All of the infinite numbers on the real line." at 11:18 is false.
Yet, "infinities of different sizes" at the end of the video suggests that the speaker knows of cardinality, and be weary of the first mistake.

¬†For students of higher math: I guess in the spirit of the talk, to see why: note 
that there are only countably many "stacked numbers," but uncountably many reals. Maybe you want to 
just get the circle? Just like a normal interval? well, the circle is 
compact, meaning it can't be a homeomorphism. Maybe you want to make it 
one? call $infty$ a number, and use the two point compactification of R (mod out by them.)
 You could however, define the surjection, perhaps most easily given by 
the equivalence relation $$a \equiv b \implies a-b \in Z$$. This is a 
really important idea, and it's just rollin the number line up into a 
circle :) Lotsa possibilites! This really would be all the real numbers "stacked on top of eachother," but uncountably many of them.

text: Here I am, a university student, wanting to resit my IGCSE maths exam cause im not accepted with a C in IGCSE mathematic in my desired profession -_-. I don't really care rnow this is extremely easy compared to A-Levels but back then this was tough lol. Kids don't be like me, actually study and try to get good grades in your igcse, they are apparently taken into account when you opt for higher end jobs such as a commercial pilot. They of course care about your A-Levels this is why you should also consider getting good grades in A-Levels as they are a very important future deciding factor, but they are also care about your IGCSE¬¥s. I applied for an airline with a grade c in igcse and a grade b in alevel maths and got rejected cause they were looking for a grade A in igcse maths as well. To me this is incredibly absurd as A-level is much harder than the simple igcse but I don't make the rules. Just putting this out there for people who were ignorant like me and been constantly told that igcse mean jack shit

text:
"Be lazy" is just a cute phrase that people in the physical sciences say to seem quirky. It's not about being lazy, and you should not strive to be lazy.

Instead, you should strive to think deeply about a problem in such a way that an elegant solution reveals itself, if at all possible. If such a solution is not possible, then your only path forward is to "brute force" the solution. Often, this brute-forcing can help reveal some pattern or abstraction that helps you discover a more elegant and clever solution to the problem.

text: I think a lot of people misunderstand his advice. It's not about being lazy, but about really seeing the problem. For example, when analyzing a double pendulum, the smart choice isn't just to write down all possible variables. Instead, you choose a coordinate system that captures only the essential parts ‚Äì the angles and lengths ‚Äì because those are the only quantities that actually influence its motion. This focus cuts away the unnecessary and reveals the problem's true structure.

text:
This is good life advice in general.

Our department has to track delivery times, with start dates and end dates entered into excel spreadsheets. Literally everyone else then manually counted the number of business days in between those two dates, by hand. It boggles my mind that I was the first person to say "hey, Microsoft Excel is a world renowned software that has been honed over the last 30 years to make the lives of accountants easier. I wonder if there's a function to automatically count business days?". Unsurprisingly, yes there is (the function is NETWORKDAYS). Now a task that would take an hour is done automatically, and more accurately than before.

text: In order to explain why I skip steps, think before starting any calculation, or use symbols instead of words when writing something down in my class, I also say that mathematicians are lazy. However, you can only give the advice to be lazy to students who study math out of real interest and with real talent. I have to teach high school mathematics and the overwhelming majority of my students are not at all interested and far from talented. If they try to be lazy, they take "shortcuts" that don't work because they are breaking the rules. They leave out important steps and fail to prove that their solution is complete. They guess more than actually thinking. So be very careful who you say this to!

text:
Engineering is fundamentally founded upon laziness.

In an electrical engineering class I took, the professor was teaching how alternating currents worked, and to illustrate the point above, used advanced calculus to determine electrical impedance of a circuit.  It took him about 20 minutes to do the calculations.  Then he used imaginary numbers and some basic algebra, and it took him about two minutes.

Later, I recall the cumbersome and lengthy algebraic way my wife was taught to do drug calculations in nursing school.  I showed her how to do them using dimensional analysis (the engineering way), and what used to take several minutes to calculate, took her less than a minute using simple arithmetic.

text: During my sophomore year in Engineering, I recall a young assistant professor/senior lecturer attempting to solve a math problem involving Laplace or Fourier transforms in class - though the exact details now escape me. Unfortunately, the teacher couldn't solve the problem within the class time and assigned it as homework. I spent nearly four and a half hours that night working through the challenge and eventually arrived at a solution, which, if I recall correctly, turned out to be '1'. The next day, I showed my solution to the faculty, and I was the only student who had solved it. However, after analyzing the solution, the faculty member announced to the class that the problem was too complex, large and unsuitable for inclusion in the semester examination for Engineering students, let alone a class test. It's worth noting that back in 2006-07, solving complex mathematical problems through the internet wasn't a thing - WolframAlpha, for instance, was probably only launched in 2009 or after...

text:
that literally means just working smarter, more effort doesn't (always) equal = to more willpower.


One person put's more effort than someone else to find a equation using a long method.

Vs someone who used a short method to find the equation.

That means the person has worked smarter, not harder.

Because the time taken to find the equation with the longer method =  more time and effort.

The smarter worked using the shorter method = less time and less effort = working smarter.

Because you found a way of getting the same result but in a shorter easier way.

That does not make the person lazy.

Finding a easier solution which takes less time = working smarter, willpower is the main factor that makes this entire process work though.


Being lazy would mean you wouldn't even be asked to do it or give up mid process. This is a huge misconception and mistaken classification that teacher had made.

This is true, but risky. Jumping 3 logical steps in one makes it blooming hard to spot the minutest of errors. Wouldn't be the first time I got a quindecuple negative wrong in my head. 
Also in Mathematics, and to a certain extent Physics, you can validly assume idealised special case assumptions which allow mathematical 'shortcuts' to be viable. By the time you get to Engineering nothing is perfect or ideal due to manufacturing or measurement capabilities, so you can't see what you're doing, let alone make it, with sufficient precision and accuracy to assert those convenient idealised mathematical assumptions can remain valid.

The lazy solution is realizing that the integrand is either an odd or an even function integrated over a symmetric interval around the origin. 

That is, integral of f(x) from -a to a where f is an even and continous function then 2 multiplied by the integral of f(x) from 0 to a or if f is an odd and continous function between -a and a then the integral of f(x) over this interval cancels to 0.

text:
Being a mathematician myself, I have believed this my entire life.

But it's important to understand it should be the _right_ kind of lazy. A mathematician shouldn't shy away from doing a lot of hard (and sometimes tedious) work if he thinks he could develop a more general method to solve a broader class of problems than is the case today.  

It's fine to be lazy if the new way actually is smarter and gives additional insight.  But not lazy as in 'I can generally work with the results of this theory, but I never quite understood the nuts and bolts of it'. Though even _that_ is OK to a certain extent - you can't specialize in everything, after all.

text:
My maths lecturer told me "find the pattern, know the solution.‚Äù

1,2,3,4,5....10 where x is the existent of the sequence, plus 1 = n, the novel of the sequence. Ergo, the pattern is n=x+1

Eg to follow the sequence if we know upto 5, then 5 is the existent of the sequence = x. To find the novel of the sequence we identify that the sequence is + 1 to the existent, so n = 5 + 1 = 6.

Of course this is over-simplified, but the general principle stands where it looks chaotic the answer you need lies in a sequence Ergo, find the pattern, know the answer.

text:
It's kinda funny how true this is. Or how true it seems to me, at least.

In the first sections of a numerical analysis book, it is likely that you will find numerical methods to get solutions of random equations that don't contain derivatives or integrals.

There is a great emphasis on speed of convergence: how fast does a method get you to an answer that's as close as possible to the real answer. Almost as if... The book was trying to progressively teach you ways to be lazy and get answers without having to spend so much paper on a single equation.

Because, all methods will get you an answer with the problems that the book provides. The only difference is the complexity of the methods and the speed at with they give you an answer. The later methods really feel like some lazy person coming up with a complex method to avoid having to do the same thing over and over and over to get an answer.

text: Ok that‚Äôs somewhat misleading. You only seem to indicate the blue area, with the blue and red pens, excluding the white slices of the circle. In that case you have to subtract the white parts of each square. Assume the blue square is 2x2 then the area is 4. Alternately you can generalize the side of the blue square to be 2x, but then the x‚Äôs cancel out. The inscribed white circle has an area of pi. Radius has to be 1. The red square is half the blue square, or two. So just the blue area is 4-pi. And then the ration of red to blue area is 2/(4-pi). Roughly 2.33.

text:
Summary:

*Why Some Struggle with Math*
- Math is viewed as the hardest subject by some, while being the easiest for others.
- Secret to ease in math: developing math sense and problem-solving skills.
- It's not about the number of formulas you know, rather, understanding the underlying principles of math.

*Role of a Good Math Tutor*
- Focus on problem-solving skills rather than just a bunch of formulas to memorize.

*Problem- Remembering vs Understanding*
- Students struggle with remembering formulas instead of comprehending the concept.
- Problem-solution skill improves with deeper understanding and reduces the number of memorized formulas.
- Math skill improvement is equivalent to enhancing skills as a construction worker rather than simply adding tools to your toolbox.

*Impact of Inadequate Teachers on Learning*
- Some teachers do not adequately explain mathematical concepts.
- Limited understanding pressure students to focus on memorization of formulas, leading to difficulties when faced with unobserved problems.

*Suggestion to Improve Math Understanding: Three-Part Solution*
 1. Break down the mathematical problem into its foundational parts: Understand the underlying parts that make up the problem.
 2. Review the tools needed for each part: Think about whether you comprehend each tool or concept, or merely recite it.  
    - If it's the latter, seek further resources to aid understanding (like Khan Academy, YouTube videos, etc.)
 3. Try to solve the problem yourself without looking at the answer key: initially resist prompt solutions and investigate connections between the problem's components, leading to powerful problem-solving skills.

*Outcome of Understanding Math*
- In-depth understanding over memorizing eases problem-solving.
- Understanding prepares you for real-life scenarios better; since solutions are seldom provided.
- Initial effort to understand the foundation will be rewarded long term.
- Becoming a master in math is achievable by understanding the subject matter.
  
*Conclusion*
- Repeat after me: "Math is not about memorizing."
- Understanding math concepts deeply is the 'real' secret to excelling in the subject.
- Following these simple steps can transform your math learning experience.

text:
I can't underscore how important it is, this fundamental test taking method (for any subject): don't allow yourself to get stuck on one problem. Especially if you are taking a test like the SATs. If you encounter an extremely difficult problem, you should feel free to skip that problem and try to get back to it after you finish all the ones you can do. Of course, if you wind up skipping every problem, then...you have problems, LOL!

I consider myself to be pretty good at math. 600 on math on SATs. And I definitely used the "skip difficult problems" method. What's really important to understand about standardized tests are: Time is your enemy. You need to maximize each second spent on each question.

According to the Khan Academy: The digital SAT Reading and Writing section consists of two 32-minute modules, for a total of 64 minutes. Each module contains 27 questions, for a total of 54 questions in the section. That means you'll have just over a minute per question.

So, look at it this way, if you spend over one minute per question, you'll probably never going to finish the SATs. This also means, that if you do not skip questions, you may never get to the last question, and potentially miss out on ones that you can solve/answer.

text: I had some great teachers of math in elementary school who helped me understand math, and geometry, from the get go.  However, i do have an amazing memory so, memorizing formulas, for me, was a piece of cake.  Memorizing arithmetic tables was facilitated by my grandmother drilling them before class.  I still remember all geometry formulas for areas and perimeters of regular polygons that I learned in 3rd grade.  My high school teacher for arithmetic, algebra, geometry and trigonometry did make us recite formulas and they stuck.  I can recite back to you binomial expansions, factorization of simple polynomials, geometry formulas, trigonometric definitions and identities.  I, then, went to engineering college and I can still recall formulas for derivatives of products and quotients, the chain rule, L‚ÄôHopital‚Äôs ruble for limits, tables of derivatives, tables of anti derivatives, integration by substitution, integration by parts, formulas from multi variate calculus, lineal algebra, vector analysis, and differential equations.  I still remember all the basic definitions of statistics of samples, and the most common parametric probability distributions from my college years.  Definitely understand math very well, but train your memory also, is a great combination.

text:
I remember at age 14 I read about perspective in drawing. If a rectangular window which is vertically divided into 2 equal parts shall be drawn so that one end, nearer us, will be higher in the drawing than the far end, where shall you put the division? The nearer half must be drawn broader than the one farther away, but where exactly shall we place the division? A simple and elegant solution is to draw the 2 diagonals - where they meet is the right place. What if the window has 4 equal parts? Simply repeat the process on each half.
Now, 60 years later, I happened to think: "What if the window has 3 equal parts?" And using some creativity I solved it. Try it! You have probably never seen any formula or algorithm for this, so you must think creatively!
(Trisecting an angle is impossible, but not a window!)

text: here are some key tips: 1. math isn't metaphysics (it can help you add apples but it can't tell you what an apple is) 2. all of math is just the addition and/or subtraction of quantities/magnitudes and it creates a bunch of shortcuts that mean the same thing (3+3+3 = 3x3 = 3 squared) 3. zero isn't a number it's a placeholder, which is why you can't add/subtract/multiply/divide by zero. 4. the point of math is to help us predict a future outcome so that we can make better decisions in the present. 5. calculus is the reason you're learning algebra and calculus is just a (rate) change in quantity/magnitude over time (instead of 3+3+3 it's 3+2+1) 5. you'll be expected to learn how to translate language into a math equation so practice interpreting what it means when the store says 30% 'off' (move the decimal over two, multiply by .3 then subtract that result from the original amount) 6. don't feel bad about not understanding something.. it took humanity over 100k years to develop what you're learning so it's not reasonable to expect 18 year olds to be more competent than the sum total of the brightest people in human history.

text:
There are three parts too good math I reckon. Firstly, knowing that every symbol in math is a mix of plus, minus, add and divide. Secondly, knowing that algebra is the rules of mathematics, and you cannot do the formulas without knowing algebra. And thirdly is the concept, having someone explain it to you so you understand the nature of the problem, so that you can visualize it in the mind; As in this video. If you have a failure in the first two, then the problem is likely the student. And if you have a failure of the third, then the problem is likely the teacher. This is the way I see it.

The problem for the student is most likely, to call out the teacher, they need a good knowledge base from the first two. But if you explain all three to a student, I reckon they should be able to skip the teacher, and discover these things on their own. There should be enough resources out there these days. They just need to swallow a bit of pride, especially if their problem is the first problem I mentioned.

So, I agree with concept in this video. But I would not call them hacks. Calling them hacks I reckon likely makes the student fell hopeless. I would call them being taught to visualize.

text:
Here's how I approached the problem:
Let the side of the red square= a and blue square= b 
To find: (a^2)/(b^2).
Now to reduce the variables in the equation I let a = 1 as no specific value is given, (even if you let a to be something else, since we are finding ratios here, it'll always reduce to the simplest form. )
now we need to find 1/(b^2).
Notice that the circle has its diameter equal to the hypotenuse of the red square. 
=> using the Pythagoras theorem we have diameter = ‚àö(1^2+1^2) = ‚àö2. 
Diameter of the circle is equal to the side of the blue square. Therefore we have, b =‚àö2 and b^2 = 2. Hence 1/(b^2) = 1/2 .

text:
This problem was quite easy, I will explain my approach for anyone interested. I started out by simply labeling the inner side length a, and the outer side length c, and used the Pythagorean theorem to get c^2 in terms of a^2 (c^2 = a^2 / 2). The ratio of the areas is simply c^2 / a^2, so using what we just found this gives us (a^2 / 2) / a^2, and the a^2 here cancel leaving us with 1/2.

The problem, just like many others, becomes elementary when you apply tools such as Pythagoras and geometric relationships. You simply have to learn intuitively when to use each tool. The basic mathematical tools will take you very far if you are proficient in using them.

text:
hi , the video was amazing .. i wanted to share what else helped me . often times we straightly jump to solving questions of the chapter which makes us bored and leaves us wondering ,, instead divide the chapter in chunks , suppose we are handling derivatives so you can start like the first thing is 
f'(x) = nx^n-1 and then practice the type of questions around this formula ... 
i also suggest deriving trigonometric and calculas formulas to understand their origin and retain them better also dig a bit deeper to understand why we made such topic , example: calculas was develped to calculate what speed , velocities or any other sort of motion on an instant such as calculating the speed at 0.000000001 sec , we tend to take limit tends to zero for this ,which implies that time is approaching 0 but cannot be exact zero itself . maths is a language trust me , the more you speak it (practice it ) the more u get it .. but the practice must be mindful .

text:
Veil's Summary Notes:

This is How To ACE Math Step-By-Step.

- It's not about how many formulas you know. Instead, it's all about your problem solving skills and math sense.

But let's start with problem solving.

- Problem = Anything that humans pretend to have a missing piece of information to.
- Solution = That 'missing' piece of information which was never missing to begin with. 
- So To solve a problem, all you have to do is express the connections of this missing piece of information that isn't really missing, but always existed within the problem's context, yet people pretend it is missing just for the sake of challenging our mental capabilities.

Getting back to math sense, don't just learn excessive amounts of formulas without understanding HOW to use them in the first place. That's where your math sense comes in. 

Note: Math Sense = Math Skills.

The greater your Math Sense, the less you need to memorize.

Your Math Sense is basically the Cheat skill that will help you solve ANY Problem that comes your way in Math.

This is HOW You Acquire it;


1. Prioritize Understanding Over Memorizing.

For example, for the square root of 25, don't worry about memorizing the fact that; "the square root of 25 is 5."

Instead, focus on understanding the actual step by step process you need to take, to find the "square root" of something.

In other words, focus on understanding the meanings of each symbols and terms, especially the steps they require you to take.

Once you do understand these MAiN symbols/figures and what steps they require you to take, then you can do practice problems with ease.

You don't need to use any advanced memorization techniques once you understand, because when you do practice problems or your homeworks and assignments, then these operations will become engraved in your memory, whether you like it or not!


2. Break Your Math Problem into Parts.

Usually, we don't understand the foundations behind bigger math problems, that's why we tend to get stuck. Therefore, doing this will help spot our gaps in knowledge.

We know when we lack a certain knowledge when we look at the individual parts within the problem, and go, "huh?"

If you don't understand some parts within that problem, then break those parts down even further untill you spot familiar concepts you can use to build on your understanding.

If you break down the parts within a problem, but still don't understand those parts, then KEEP Breaking Those Parts Down Further! Keep breaking them down to something sooo basic, that it is impossible for you to NOT understand it.


3. Review Fundamentals on a Deeper Level.

After you've understood the fundamentals of each parts within the problem on the previous step, now is the time to solidify those concepts!

Watch some extra videos or do some extra research to clarify why the steps work, as well as their origins.

This will deepen your understanding.

You can also do practice problems to test, strengthen, and gain feedback for your understanding. Either use materials provided by your teachers or find free resources online.

Note that these are fundamental problems and NOT similar to the original problem you were dealing with. These little problems are to help you gain an basic understanding inorder to add to the original problem you were working on. For example, you'll work on 1+1=2 as your fundamental problems before moving to your original problem, which could be something like 12+13=25.

Repeat this step as much as you feel like it. Your internal feeling of certainty will be your guide.


4. Put The Pieces Together, and Then Reference The Solution.

Basically, try solving the original question yourself, as well as others similar to it once you've nailed the fundamental practice problems. 

Do this without looking at the answer key.

If you get to a part and feel stuck, you still must NOT look at the answer key... Yet.

Because the mental strain you feel is How your brain forces itself to access the recent understandings you've just created during the first few steps leading up to here.

Staying in this state of discomfort whilst forcing yourself to figure it out (even if your answer key is right on the next page) will pay dividends later toward your Math Sense.

Only after a long while (over 20 minutes of being stuck on the same step) do you check the answe key. But before that, try do the following within your 20 minutes;

A) Write down everything you know that could be relevant.
B) Draw connections between what you know. You can use arrows or lines to show these.
C) Make your best attempt, showcasing the full thought process you have regarding the potential solution. Give your best guess here.

After doing these 3 do you check the answer key. You can then compare the provided solutions against your own, and  see how similar or different they are.

This is where the problem-solving skills get built, and your Math Sense as well.

Lastly, Math is NOT Memorizing. 
Knowing HOW Math Works will make you the master of your math class, and NOT the victim of difficult equations.

. . .
